Hot hardbreads were sold in many typical village taverns,<ref>{{Cite web/Candlekeep forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2006)/Public Dining and Menus}}<ref> often in winter when food became scarce. One dish was slices of hardbread fried in [[leek]] butter, usually served in poor, cheap, or rural places.

Hardbread was also a staple of traveling armies, together with [[stew]], leading to the saying in [[Common]] that "armies march on bread and the bowl."<ref>{{Cite web/Candlekeep forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2006)/Pit Fighting and Military Meals}} Army cooks would bake or buy many rolls of hardbread before setting off.{{Cite web/Candlekeep forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2007)/Military Food and Supply}}

For sweet dishes, hardbread buns or loaves studded with [[currant]]s were enjoyed as a morningfeast meal. These were sometimes cut into fingers. It was a growing trend to dip these into the drink known as [[thrusk]] in the mid–14{{th}} century [[DR]].{{Cite web/Candlekeep forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2009)/Thrusk}} For a plain dessert, such as found in rural inns and small-town restaurants, hardbread slices could be sprinkled with [[sugar]] or spread with jams made from local berries.{{Cite web/theedverse/2019-10-06 - Four-course meals of the Realms}}
